soc.client

Class MessageHandler

  • java.lang.Object
    • soc.client.MessageHandler
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    SOCMessageDispatcher

    public final class MessageHandler
extends java.lang.Object
implements SOCMessageDispatcher
    Nested class for processing incoming messages (treating). ClientNetwork's reader thread calls handle(SOCMessage, Connection) to dispatch messages to their handler methods (such as handleBANKTRADE(SOCBankTrade)).

    Before v2.0.00, most of these fields and methods were part of the main SOCPlayerClient class.

    Since:
    2.0.00
    Author:
    paulbilnoski

      • dispatch

        public void dispatch(SOCMessage message,
                     Connection connection)
              throws java.lang.IllegalStateException
        Description copied from interface: SOCMessageDispatcher
        Remove a queued incoming message from a client, and handle it. Called from the message handler thread of Connection.

        Do not block or sleep in any derived code because this is single-threaded. Any slow or lengthy work for a message should be done on other threads.

        dispatch(..) must catch any exception thrown by conditions or bugs in server or gameName code it calls.

        The first message from a peer is dispatched by SOCMessageDispatcher.dispatchFirst(SOCMessage, Connection).

        Security Note: When there is a choice, always use local information over information from the message. For example, use the nickname from the connection to get the player information rather than the player information from the message. This makes it harder to send false messages making players do things they didn't want to do.

        Specified by:
        dispatch in interface SOCMessageDispatcher
        Parameters:
        message - Message from the client. Will never be null.
        connection - Connection (peer) sending this message. Will never be null.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalStateException - if not ready to dispatch because some initialization method needs to be called first;

      • handleGAMESTATE

        protected void handleGAMESTATE(SOCGame game,
                               GameState newState)
        Handle game state message: Update SOCGame and PlayerClientListener if any. Call for any message type which contains a Game State field.

        Checks current SOCGame.getGameState(); if current state is GameState.NEW_GAME and newState != NEW_GAME, calls PlayerClientListener.gameStarted() before its usual PlayerClientListener.gameStateChanged(GameState) call.

        Parameters:
        game - Game to update state; not null
        newState - New state from message, like GameState.ROLL_OR_CARD, or 0. Does nothing if 0.
        Since:
        2.0.00
        See Also:
        handleGAMESTATE(SOCGameState)

      • handleCANCELBUILDREQUEST

        protected void handleCANCELBUILDREQUEST(SOCCancelBuildRequest mes)
        handle the rare "cancel build request" message; usually not sent from server to client.

        - When sent from client to server, CANCELBUILDREQUEST means the player has changed their mind about spending resources to build a piece. Only allowed during normal game play (PLACING_ROAD, PLACING_SETTLEMENT, or PLACING_CITY).

        When sent from server to client:

        - During game startup (START1B or START2B):
        Sent from server, CANCELBUILDREQUEST means the current player wants to undo the placement of their initial settlement.

        - During piece placement (PLACING_ROAD, PLACING_CITY, PLACING_SETTLEMENT, PLACING_FREE_ROAD1 or PLACING_FREE_ROAD2):

        Sent from server, CANCELBUILDREQUEST means the player has sent an illegal PUTPIECE (bad building location). Humans can probably decide a better place to put their road, but robots must cancel the build request and decide on a new plan.

        Our client can ignore this case, because the server also sends a text message that the human player is capable of reading and acting on. For convenience, during initial placement PlayerClientListener.buildRequestCanceled(SOCPlayer) is called to reset things like SOCBoardPanel hovering pieces.

        Parameters:
        mes - the message
        Since:
        1.1.00

      • handleDEVCARDACTION

        protected void handleDEVCARDACTION(SOCDevCardAction mes)
        Handle the "development card action" message, which may have multiple cards. Updates game data by calling handleDEVCARDACTION(SOCGame, SOCPlayer, boolean, int, int), then calls PlayerClientListener.playerDevCardsUpdated(SOCPlayer, boolean).

        If message is about the player's own cards at end of game when server reveals all VP cards (SOCDevCardAction.ADD_OLD in state GameState.GAME_OVER), returns immediately and doesn't call those methods.

        Parameters:
        mes - the message

      • handleDEVCARDACTION

        protected void handleDEVCARDACTION(SOCGame ga,
                                   SOCPlayer player,
                                   boolean isClientPlayer,
                                   int act,
                                   int ctype)
        Handle one dev card's game data update for handleDEVCARDACTION(soc.message.SOCDevCardAction). In case this is part of a list of cards, does not call PlayerClientListener.playerDevCardsUpdated(SOCPlayer, boolean): Caller must do so afterwards. For SOCDevCardAction.PLAY, calls SOCPlayer.updateDevCardsPlayed(int).
        Parameters:
        ga - Game being updated
        player - Player in ga being updated
        isClientPlayer - True if player is our client playing in ga
        act - Action being done: SOCDevCardAction.DRAW, PLAY, ADD_OLD, or ADD_NEW
        ctype - Type of development card from SOCDevCardConstants
        See Also:
        SOCDisplaylessPlayerClient.handleDEVCARDACTION(SOCGame, SOCPlayer, int, int)

      • handleGAMEOPTIONINFO

        void handleGAMEOPTIONINFO(SOCGameOptionInfo mes)
        process the "game option info" message by calling ServerGametypeInfo.receiveInfo(SOCGameOptionInfo, SOCStringManager). If all are now received, possibly show game info/options window for new game or existing game.

        For a summary of the flags and variables involved with game options, and the client/server interaction about their values, see ServerGametypeInfo.

        When first connected to a server having a different version, the client negotiates available options. To avoid hanging on this process because of a very slow network or bug, SwingMainDisplay.GameOptionsTimeoutTask can eventually call this method to signal that all options have been received.

        Since:
        1.1.07
